Environment Minister Rachmat Witoelar acknowledges the prolonged flow of mud, affecting thousands.
Bakrie insists the non-toxic mud can be disposed of at sea, deflecting blame to a distant earthquake.
Indonesian officials dispute the link between the mud volcano and drilling activities, despite UN warnings of ecological damage.
Airlines adjust routes due to the disaster, with Sriwijaya Air facing delays.
British experts attribute the eruption to gas drilling, prompting legal action against Lapindo Brantas Inc. Efforts to contain the mudflow with concrete balls face skepticism from geologists.
President Yudhoyono pledges compensation for victims and environmental restoration.
